Kafka Consumer receives a deployment event.

The consumer creates an execution document in Mongo with status=pending.

The consumer creates an Agenda job, for example process-deployment, and passes only the executionId.

The consumer commits the Kafka offset and finishes quickly.

Agenda stores the job in Mongo and is responsible for waking up a worker.

The Agenda worker receives the job.

The worker loads the execution by executionId.

The worker tries to claim the execution with an atomic update: status pending -> running.

If the execution is not pending, the worker stops, because it was already handled or is already running.

If the claim succeeds, the worker processes the whole execution.

The worker fetches the project databases.

The worker creates an in-memory cache for this execution only.

The worker fetches database configs using Bottleneck to limit external API calls.

Each config is fetched once per execution and reused from the in-memory cache if needed.

The worker saves config snapshots/results to Mongo.

The worker compares the configs and detects drift.

The worker saves the comparison results/diffs.

The worker updates the execution status to completed, completed_with_drift, partial, or failed.

Agenda controls how many executions can run in parallel.

Bottleneck controls how many config API calls can run in parallel inside each execution.

The executions collection remains the business source of truth.

Agenda is only the technical job runner.